# Admin resources

Resources are declarative `defineResource(...)` definitions consumed by the admin and the generic CRUD API.

## Anatomy (see `apps/api/src/resources/posts.resource.ts` for a canonical example)

```ts
import { defineResource } from "@openadminjs/core";

export default defineResource({
  name: "posts",                    // URL segment, must be kebab/snake unique
  label: { en: "Posts", ru: "..." },// localized labels (en + ru minimum)
  model: "post",                    // Prisma model name (camelCase)
  titleField: "title",              // shown in lists/relations
  icon: "FileText",                 // lucide-react icon
  permissions: { read, create, update, delete, ...customAction },
  fields: { /* per-column metadata */ },
  actions: { /* row-level custom actions */ },
});
```

## Field metadata rules

- Every field needs a `type` and a localized `label`. Hide auto-managed fields from create/edit forms with `create: false, edit: false`.
- `searchable`, `sortable`, `filterable` are opt-in — don't enable them on heavy columns (richtext, JSON, large text).
- Relation fields: set `resource` (target resource name) and `displayField` (label in dropdowns).
- File/image fields use `resource: "files"`.

## Permissions

- Strings follow `resource.action`. Use the same names in seed roles and in `@openadminjs/permissions`.
- Custom actions must declare a `permission` and a `handler(ctx)` returning the updated record.

## Registering

- New resource files in `apps/api/src/resources/` are picked up via `registry.ts`. Keep registry imports alphabetical.
- For programmatic generation, prefer the CLI: `pnpm exec openadminjs generate resource <Model>`.

## Don'ts

- Don't put business logic in field config — keep `fields` declarative; behavior goes into `actions` or service classes.
- Don't access Prisma directly in admin UI; the generic CRUD endpoints already cover list/create/update/delete.
